04850nam a22006855i 9780814770139DE-B159720200608045044.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200608t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147701397 a10.18574/97808147701392doi  a(DE-B1597)547581  a(OCoLC)860626222  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHV6250.4.W65b.G4722 2016 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a303.60122300aGender, Violence, and Human Security :bCritical Feminist Perspectives /cAili Mari Tripp, Myra Marx Ferree, Christina Ewig. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Acronyms -- t1. Toward a Gender Perspective on Human Security -- t2. What Does Postconflict Security Mean for Women? -- t3. Gendering Insecurities, Informalization, and "War Economies" -- t4. Securitizing Sex, Bodies, and Borders -- t5. Work and Love in the Gendered U.S. Insecurity State -- t6. A Struggle for Rites -- t7. From German Bus Stop to Academy Award Nomination -- t8. Feminist Collaboration with the State in Response to Sexual Violence -- t9. The Vulnerable Protecting the Vulnerable -- t10. Violence against Women, Human Security, and Human Rights of Women and Girls -- t11. Integrating Gender into Human Security -- t12. The Discursive Politics of Gendering Human Security -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe nature of human security is changing globally: interstate conflict and even intrastate conflict may be diminishing worldwide, yet threats to individuals and communities persist. Large-scale violence by formal and informal armed forces intersects with interpersonal and domestic forms of violence in mutually reinforcing ways. Gender, Violence, and Human Security takes a critical look at notions of human security and violence through a feminist lens, drawing on both theoretical perspectives and empirical examinations through case studies from a variety of contexts around the globe.This fascinating volume goes beyond existing feminist international relations engagements with security studies to identify not only limitations of the human security approach, but also possible synergies between feminist and human security approaches. Noted scholars Aili Mari Tripp, Myra Marx Ferree, and Christina Ewig, along with their distinguished group of contributors, analyze specific case studies from around the globe, ranging from post-conflict security in Croatia to the relationship between state policy and gender-based crime in the United States. Shifting the focus of the term "human security" from its defensive emphasis to a more proactive notion of peace, the book ultimately calls for addressing the structural issues that give rise to violence. A hard-hitting critique of the ways in which global inequalities are often overlooked by human security theorists, Gender, Violence, and Human Security presents a much-needed intervention into the study of power relations throughout the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aFeminist theory. 0aHuman security. 0aWomenxViolence against. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aEwig, Christina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFerree, Myra Marx, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTripp, Aili Mari, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814770139423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814770139.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  